Happy Valentine's day from Bengi and Benga ♥️♥️ :)

Meet them this 11th of March. Mark your Calendars!

Sharing the official trailer of our film #Boroxun. 

The lack of rains and a dying river has put the lives of the inhabitants of a remote fisherman’s village at stake. Deprived of their main source of income and finding it increasingly difficult to sustain themselves, the villagers who have consulted oracles and conducted “frog-weddings” are now desperately looking for a way out of their plight. An unusual solution presented by a priest seems like a possible cure for the curse and though reluctant at first, the villagers decide to go ahead with it for the greater good of the village. Village simpletons nicknamed Benga and Bengi, suddenly find themselves at the centre of the chaos that ensues - and it changes their lives forever.

Coming to select auditoriums on the 11th of March. Looking forward to your support. :)

It is with a lot of nervous excitement I'd like to share that our debut feature film Boroxun is FINALLY set to release across Assam (eeeeeeeeeep!!). We are mostly a  young cast and crew who've come together for their debut under the generous support of @saj_entertainment . We seek your support, love and wishes over the next few weeks as we gear for the film's release. Dates will be announced shortly. #Boroxun coming real soon now. :)

latestPosts.caption:
Here’s a glimpse into the first part of our three-part travelogue, filmed in Longwa—a remote village in Nagaland that straddles the India–Myanmar border. Home to the Konyaks, a warrior tribe once known for headhunting, Longwa is led by the Angh, a chief who claims authority over 35 villages—30 in Myanmar’s Sagaing region and 5 in India’s Mon district. With the Indian government’s recent decision to fence the border, the village has taken a firm stand against the move, which threatens to divide its land, people, and identity.

In this episode, we join the Konyaks in celebrating Aoleang Monyu—their spring festival and traditional New Year. Through food, customs, song, and dance, we explore living traditions and hear stories from the last of the headhunters. Even amid the festivities, the Konyaks remain resolute, using the celebration as a platform to reaffirm their unity and resist the border fencing.

LINK IN BIO.

I didn’t know who is she, when I saw her. I was just drawn in by her energy—short hair, traditional wrap with a modern twist, and the way she owned the space effortlessly. I took the shots without hesitation. Later, I checked her profile… It turns out, she’s a star bro. And when I saw how these shots came out—I knew I did something sick. It’s crazy how magic happens when you follow your gut and let the moment lead.

— UnrevealedStories
